      "id": "vblA",
      "code_hash": "e2c276606d4b3bce04c862cabe3f80fe",
      "outputs": [
        {
          "type": "data",
          "data": {
            "text/markdown": "<span class=\"markdown prose dark:prose-invert contents\"><h1 id=\"arc-easy-prompt-repetition-experiment\">ARC-Easy: Prompt Repetition Experiment</h1>\n<span class=\"paragraph\">This notebooks serves two purposes.</span>\n<ol>\n<li>It reproduces the \"repeat the prompt\" technique from <a href=\"https://www.alphaxiv.org/abs/2512.14982\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\">the \"Prompt Repetition Improves Non-Reasoning LLMs\" paper</a>. The idea is to transform a prompt, like <code>&lt;QUERY&gt;</code>, into <code>&lt;QUERY&gt; &lt;QUERY&gt;</code> or <code>&lt;QUERY&gt; &lt;QUERY&gt; &lt;QUERY&gt;</code>. It's a stange-trick, but one that seems to work. So this notebook tries to reproduce the finding on open-source models on the Arc-Easy task.</li>\n<li>It also serves to display a general pattern. Notebooks are great for exploration, but marimo also makes it great to serve as a batch job. Combine it with weights and biases and suddenly you have a nice way to run larger experiments.</li>\n</ol>\n<h2 id=\"design\">Design</h2>\n<span class=\"paragraph\">This notebook is designed to be run as a command line application as well. You can run it via:</span>\n<div class=\"language-text codehilite\"><pre><span></span><code>uv run arc-easy-llm.py --repeat-count 2\n</code></pre></div>\n<span class=\"paragraph\">All the parameters defined in the  <code>ExperimentParams</code> pydantic class can be passed via the command line as well.</span>\n<h2 id=\"experiment\">Experiment</h2>\n<span class=\"paragraph\">The parameters for the experience are defined in a <code>pydantic</code> base model below. Make sure to change the project name for your own.</span></span>"
          }
        }
      ],
      "console": []
    },
